                        <bindingDesc>
                            <binding>
                                <decoNote xml:id="b1" type="SlipCase">Contained in a box together with two more manuscripts 
                                    (<ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BLorient3716a">London, British Library, BL Oriental 3716 a</ref> and <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BLorient3761c">BLorient3761c</ref>).</decoNote>
                            </binding>
                        </bindingDesc>
                        <accMat>
                            <desc>In the box containing this manuscript togeter with <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BLorient3716a">London, British Library, BL Oriental 3716 a</ref> and
                                <ref type="mss" corresp="https://betamasaheft.eu/BLorient3761c">BLorient3761c</ref> is also found a leaf of paper (270x220mm), written on both recto and verso 
                                and dated in <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1212Addigr">Addigrat</placeName> 
                                to <date when="1868-05-18">18 May 1868</date> with an English translation of an Ethiopic charm for protecting the 
                                mule of <persName role="owner" ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14543KidanaMaryam">Kidāna Māryām</persName> by 
                                <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14542WilberforceCl"><roleName type="title">Lieutenant</roleName> H. Wilberforce Clarke</persName>.
                                The translation is preceded by an introductory explanation and followed by brief remarks.</desc>
                            <q xml:lang="en">Translation of an Ethiopic Charm, found tied round the neck of a mule, brought for sale into the Camp of 
                                <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC1212Addigr">Addigerāt</placeName>, in Abyssinia, on the occasion of a British Army 
                                being in the field, in that country, for the purpose of rescuing from Captivity and Chains, several Englishmen and others, 
                                wrongfully and forcibly detained, at <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC4547Maqdal">Magdala</placeName>,
                                by <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9430Tewodros">Theodore, or Tédros</persName>, the renowned King of the 
                                Abyssinians. <gap reason="ellipsis"/> The above was translated, from the Tigré Language, into broken English, by
                                <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS14541PeterBrru">Peter Brru</persName>, a native of Abyssinia, who, from fear of 
                                <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS9430Tewodros">Tédros</persName>, King of the Abyssinians fled the Country. He became a 
                                merchant, at <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC4631Massaw">Massowah</placeName>, on the shores of the Red-Sea. 
                                Eventually, going to Malta, he was engaged as Interpreter to the British Force sent into Abyssinia, to rescue the European
                                Prisoners, at <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC4547Maqdal">Magdala</placeName>, in <date when="1867">1867</date>.</q>
                        </accMat>
